[
    {
        "content": "<p>It's well known (and in mathlib) that the dual Pᵛ of a finite projective R-module P is also finite projective. When trying to generalize <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/LinearAlgebra/Dual.html#Module.finite_dual_iff\">Module.finite_dual_iff</a> from free modules to projective modules, I investigated all possible implications between (conjunctions of) the four conditions <code>Finite R P</code>, <code>Finite R Pᵛ</code>, <code>Projective R P</code> and <code>Projective R Pᵛ</code>; 3 of the 12 binary implications appear harder than the others, and I've only figured out one of them so far. These look like some good puzzles to test one's intuition, so I'm posting them as a poll. If you are able to construct counterexamples or give proofs, they are of course appreciated.</p>",
        "id": 491532030,
        "sender_full_name": "Junyan Xu",
        "timestamp": 1735769055
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>/poll Which of the following always hold?</p>\n<p>Projective R P ∧ Finite R Pᵛ → Finite R P<br>\nProjective R P ∧ Finite R Pᵛ ↛ Finite R P<br>\nProjective R P ∧ Finite R Pᵛ → Projective R Pᵛ<br>\nProjective R P ∧ Finite R Pᵛ ↛ Projective R Pᵛ<br>\nProjective R Pᵛ ∧ Finite R P → Finite R Pᵛ<br>\nProjective R Pᵛ ∧ Finite R P ↛ Finite R Pᵛ</p>",
        "id": 491532076,
        "sender_full_name": "Junyan Xu",
        "timestamp": 1735769125
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Shouldn't we have options which are the negations of current options?</p>",
